# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 17:47:08
overview:<p>The Cerberus is a ninety-five-ton assault BattleMech produced by LexaTech Industries, introduced in 3054 from the company's facility on Hun Ho in the Draconis Combine. Conceived as LexaTech's bid to create a design worthy of competing with classic Star League-era assault 'Mechs like the King Crab and Atlas, the Cerberus was built around a philosophy of combining heavy long-range firepower with speed unusual for its weight class. The design's massive engine propels the 'Mech to speeds approaching sixty-five kilometers per hour, making it one of the fastest assault 'Mechs in production. LexaTech used the Cerberus to successfully diversify into the conventional heavy BattleMech market during the post-Clan Invasion rearmament period.</p>

capabilities:<p>Firepower appears to have been the sole consideration driving the Cerberus design. For long- and medium-range engagements, it carries two devastating Grizzard Model 200 Gauss rifles, one mounted in each arm. Though such powerful weapons were in limited supply during the design phase, the advantage of possessing such awesome firepower overrode any objections, and with several well-placed shots a Cerberus can cripple virtually any opponent. Supporting these heavy weapons, a quartet of Blankenburg medium pulse lasers lurks behind well-concealed fire doors on the 'Mech's upper torso, sliding away during combat to extend the lasers' field of fire. A favored tactic involves waiting until an unsuspecting foe closes to point-blank range before deploying these close-combat weapons to devastating effect.</p><p>The Cerberus achieves its exceptional speed through the massive GM 380 XL engine, but this comes at the price of only eleven tons of Aldis Heavy ferro-fibrous armor protecting the chassis, a meager amount for a ninety-five-ton assault 'Mech. Designers included a pair of rear-firing Sperry Browning machine guns for anti-infantry defense and a head-mounted McArthur anti-missile system to provide protection against missile attacks. The reinforced lower torso and legs provide a strong and steady firing platform, but pilots must exercise caution in close-quarters engagements where the 'Mech's thin armor can be quickly exploited by concentrated fire.</p>

deployment:<p>Appearing in 3055, this variant is a refit variant fielded by the Free Worlds League and the Word of Blake, who also designated it the MNT-A-RY-5M. This modification replaces the right-arm Gauss rifle with an extended-range PPC, freeing sufficient weight to increase armor protection to fourteen tons and add three additional double heat sinks along with two more medium pulse lasers. While sacrificing some of the raw hitting power of the twin-Gauss configuration, this variant gains substantially improved durability and heat management, making it better suited to sustained engagements where the original's thin armor proved a liability.</p>

history:<p>The Cerberus was born from LexaTech Industries' ambition to produce a powerful assault 'Mech in the tradition of the classic Star League designs. LexaTech, long recognized as the Draconis Combine's foremost manufacturer of Land-Air 'Mechs at their Irece facility, had lost that plant to Clan Nova Cat during the invasion of 3051. Seeking to rebuild and diversify, the company turned its Hun Ho facility toward developing a new heavy assault design. After more than a year of intensive engineering effort, the Cerberus entered production in 3054.</p><p>With the Inner Sphere still reeling from the Clan Invasion, LexaTech found an eager market for their new design. Cashing in on the rearmament frenzy, the company was willing to sell the Cerberus to virtually anyone, Inner Sphere Great Houses, minor nobles, and well-heeled mercenary commands alike. This open sales policy allowed the Cerberus to spread rapidly across the Inner Sphere and beyond. Though the initial enthusiasm prompted by the 'Mech's raw firepower eventually cooled as buyers gained experience with its thin armor protection, demand remained high throughout the Clan Invasion era and into the Civil War period.</p><p>The Free Worlds League and Word of Blake both adopted the Cerberus and developed their own modified variant, the MR-5M, which traded one Gauss rifle for improved survivability. The Word of Blake later took this further with the MR-6B modification at Gibson, incorporating their signature improved C3 computer for network-centric warfare. Meanwhile, the straightforward MR-V3 field refit proved popular across factions, with units simply stripping the machine guns to bolster armor protection.</p><p>During the Jihad, the Hun Ho facility continued production under Draconis Combine control. By 3079, the plant was operating at approximately ninety percent of its pre-Jihad capacity, having suffered no combat losses, a sign of the facility's remote location near the Bergen continent's polar region. However, the military drawdowns of the early Republic era saw the plant primarily mothballed, with only limited production of spare parts maintained. The MR-V2 production line fell silent.</p><p>The collapse of the HPG network in 3132 prompted the Draconis Combine to reactivate the Hun Ho facility and restore full production capacity. LexaTech introduced the modernized MR-7K in the 3120s, incorporating Endo Steel construction and anti-ballistic armor to keep the venerable design competitive with contemporary assault 'Mechs. The Cerberus continues to serve across the Inner Sphere as a formidable long-range fire support platform, its twin Gauss rifles remaining as fearsome as when the design first rolled off the assembly line on Hun Ho decades earlier.</p>

